                        Douglas
                    ) to the Secretary of
                            State</title></titleStmt><sourceDesc><bibl type="frus-volume-id">frus1949v08</bibl><bibl type="frus-document-id">d976</bibl><bibl type="frus-document-number">976</bibl><bibl type="frus-div-subtype">historical-document</bibl></sourceDesc></fileDesc><profileDesc><settingDesc><setting><date notBefore="1949-08-09T13:00:00-05:00" notAfter="1949-08-09T13:00:00-05:00"/></setting></settingDesc></profileDesc></teiHeader><text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1949-08-09T13:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1949-08-09T13:00:00-05:00" n="976" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d976">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">701.0093/8–949: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in the United Kingdom</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Douglas</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1949-08-09T19:00:00+01:00">August 9, 1949—7 p. m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received August 9—4:14 p. m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>3137. According Dening,<note n="54" xml:id="d976fn54">Maberly E. Dening, British
                        Assistant Under-Secretary of State for Foreign Affairs (Far East).</note>
                    Foreign Office, Canadian Ambassador originally suggested those ambassadors
                    remaining China announce concurrently their impending withdrawal but timing
                    departure left convenience individual ambassador. British Ambassador so informed
                    Foreign Office and recommended concurrence (Nanking 12 [<hi rend="italic">2</hi>], August 6<note n="55" xml:id="d976fn55">Same as telegram No. 1729 from
                        Nanking, <hi rend="italic">supra</hi>.</note>). Foreign Office reaction
                    unfavorable as placing too much importance on “unrecognition”. No decision,
                    however, in absence Bevin.<note n="56" xml:id="d976fn56">Ernest Bevin, British
                        Secretary of State for Foreign Affairs.</note>
                </p>
                <p>Repeated Nanking, Canton.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Douglas</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
